   "source": [
    "Iterators - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "1c6e627c-b47a-4fc9-9b28-83ce3bb9d7f3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Where we are at so far...\n",
    "\n",
    "We have created a custom container type object with __next__ method\n",
    "But several drawbacks\n",
    "-> cannot use a for loop\n",
    "-> once we start using next no going back\n",
    "-> once we have reached StopIteration we are done with the object\n",
    "\n",
    "Tackle loop issue first\n",
    "We saw how to iterate using __next__, StopIteation, and a while loop\n",
    "This is how Python handles for loops in general\n",
    "We need to tell Python that our class has that __next__ method and that it will behave in a consistent way using a while loop to iterate\n",
    "Python knows we have __next__, but how does it know we implement StopIteration?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "36e97c01-e714-427a-b47f-111f76848623",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Iterator Protocol\n",
    "\n",
    "A protocol is a fancy way of saying our class is going to implement certain functionality that Python can count on\n",
    "To let Python know our class can be iterated over using __next__ we implement the iterator protocol\n",
    "\n",
    "Iterator protocol is simple - the class needs to implement two methods:\n",
    "__iter__ -> method should resturn the object (class instance) itself (sounds weird)\n",
    "__next__ -> method is responsible for handing back next element and raising StopIteration exception when all elements have been handed out\n",
    "\n",
    "An object that implements these two methods is called an iterator"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "adf690cd-e7bf-480a-98bd-d9f1800c7369",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterators\n",
    "\n",
    "Iterator is therefore an object that implements:\n",
    "__iter__ -> returns object itself\n",
    "__next__ -> return next item from container or raises StopIteration\n",
    "\n",
    "If an object is an iterator, we can use it with for loops, comprehensions, etc..\n",
    "Python will know how to loop (iterate) over such an object (basically using same while loop technique)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "987a60b3-b30f-4b9f-b6e3-bd73c77232a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Going back to Squares example and making it an iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "class Squares:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, length):\n",
    "        self.i = 0\n",
    "        self.length = length\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__(self):\n",
    "        if self.i >= self.length:\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            result = self.i ** 2\n",
    "            self.i += 1\n",
    "            return result\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = Squares(5)\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in sq:\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "0\n",
    "1\n",
    "4\n",
    "9\n",
    "16\n",
    "\n",
    "Still one issue, iterator cannot be restarted, iterator exhausted\n",
    "To loop a second time we have to create a new instance and loop through that"
   ]
  }
 ],
